morgenthau 🇵🇰 01-Jul-20 09:48 PM
@Syed Raza , one good way to plan your courses is to make a degree planner on excel of google sheets. I'm going to share a screenshot of the one I've made for myself, and give some pointers on how you can go about making one for yourself
1
1. replicate this table in a spreadsheet 2. fill out the details of the courses that you have already completed 3. find out the details of all the remaining courses you have to complete by completing the following steps: - go to https://london.ac.uk/courses - find your degree program and select it. this should take you to a new page - scroll down and click 'Program Structure, Courses' - select thestandard route option.
Course Finder
4. You will now be able to see a list of all the required courses you have to complete. Add all of those to the table, including any pre-requisites that they may have. You can find the pre-reqs by clicking the individual course.
6. See details of requirements regarding elective courses. Choose the desired courses and then add them to the table
7. Please make sure that in most cases, you cannot have more than five 100 levels courses
8. if you're studying with an institute, you might have to align the courses with their availability at your institute
Good luck! If you have any difficulties, feel free to reach out and I can help you in finalising your plan.
Syed Raza 01-Jul-20 10:06 PM

Gundabadwarg 05-Jul-20 04:10 PM
Do you know if we have to reference the fact that we are writing from the study guide? I didnt think so, then i overthought it and now i am not sure.
morgenthau 🇵🇰 05-Jul-20 07:38 PM
reference anything that isn't your original idea or if you're copying from simewhere. Turnitin picks up everything so you wanna be on the safe side
Do you know if we have to reference the fact that we are writing from the study guide? I didnt think so, then i overthought it and now i am not sure.
@Gundabadwarg
Gundabadwarg 05-Jul-20 07:39 PM
Thanks
Can i like change the words a lot and write the same stuff?
morgenthau 🇵🇰 05-Jul-20 07:43 PM
see it depends. If its something that you feel that you could come up with yourself or is common sense/knowledge, then sure. But if its something that is not possible for you to know unless you read it somewhere, then reference it regardless of how many words you change. for example, lets say you're in a political science paper and are about to define the term "political sociology", then no matter how many words you move around, the examiner knows you read it somewhere. So after defining it, just add the original authors name in parantheses. However, if you're saying something like "politics is very important for well functioning societies bla bla", then it is okay not to reference it (as long as it isn't copy pasted). Hope that made sense
1

morgenthau 🇵🇰 21-Jul-20 06:14 PM
Exams still not over for me but I'll share my story nonetheless. I'm pursuing a degree in International Relations. From a very young age, I was fascinated by how states interact with one another and eventually how and why they go to war. Part of this also had to do with the fact that I was born in a military family. In the late 1990s, when the Lahore-Islamabad Motorway opened in Pakistan, I would spend the entire 4-5 hour long journey discussing Hitler's Biltzkrieg strategies with my father. As an 8 year old, I was fascinated with the speed with which the German army was able to conquer France, Poland etc. I then discussed the effectiveness of a such a stratgy in case of a war between Pakistan and India. Fast forward a decade and I was pursuing a degree in Mechnical Engineering. This was mostly due to the fact that Pakistani educational culture views engineering and medcine as more respecatble professions. Also, back then, with the low penetration of the internet, I had no idea that such fields even existed. It wasn't until I was taking a mandatory course on American Government and wrote a paper on Political Socialisation when my professor said "What are you doing in engineering school? You are a pure liberal arts and social sciences students." Of course it was too late to quit then but I always carried her words with me. When I came back to Pakistan in 2016, I decided to pursue a masters in Political Science from a local university. Completed the masters and started exploring online programs in IR when I stumbled upon UoL. It seemed like a perfect fit for me to expand my knowledge and then pursure a higher degree in the UK. (edited)
Enrolled in the program in 2018, got married a few months later. Despite working and studying (independently) at the same time, I was able to do really well in my first year examinations. I was able to get a Top in the World in one subject, and one of the best EMFSS scores all across Pakistan. A major chunk of credit goes to my wife for supporting my passion and helping me stay focused. A lot has happened between the my exams last year and this year. In February, I was blessed with a baby daughter. Unsurprisingly, babies are not as understanding as adults and my daughter punctuated my study sessions with crying, milk-spills and what not. Yet, once again, I was able to manage everything because of the support of my family members. I have my third exam tomorrow, and the last on the 30th. Hopefully I can do well enough to apply to the grad school of my choice. I understand that this community has many people like me, mature learners who resumed studying after a significant gap. Yet, from what Iâ€™ve been able to make out, the vast majority of you are in your first academic programs. The reason I shared my story is to hopefully inspire some of you to not give up on what you are passionate about. This doesnâ€™t mean that youâ€™ll be able to pursue your objectives at your time of choosing. Life has the tendency to throw curveballs such as finances, family issues, and, as weâ€™ve found out this year, pandemics that can derail us in pursuit of our goals. But this doesnâ€™t have to be permanent. You will find that with perseverance, you will be able to eventually get to your goal. Thank you for reading if you made it this far. Thank you to everyone who shared resources with me over the past few months. Good luck to all of you for your result. May it help you in fulfilling your future dreams and aspirations. (edited)

morgenthau 🇵🇰 21-Jul-20 10:46 PM
>
Wow! @morgenthau 🇵🇰 your story is inspirational! I too have an inclination towards IR but I have no idea why I chose Bsc Economics and Management. But Iâ€™d love to expand my knowledge on IR and political science. Can you recommend me resources for a beginner like me so I can learn on my own? @Ilsa Tariq thank you for your kind words. Based on the courses that you are likely to have taken in your first year, I think you can still switch as those courses can count towards your electives.
>
As far as expanding your knowledge about IR and Pol Sci is concerned, I would suggest reading the subject guides of PS1130 (Intro to Modern Political Thought) and then IR1011 (Intro to IR). This is because PS1130 will give you a theoretical framework of modern IR scholarship, specifically the theories of IR. All this will then help you in ascribing to the school of thought that makes most sense to you.
>
Another beneift of the study guides is that the material is summarised so it makes for easy introductory reading. Furthermore, there is a lot of guidance about supplementary reading material.
>
Hope that was helpful. Please feel free to reach out if you have any other questions.
morgenthau 🇵🇰 21-Jul-20 10:55 PM
@morgenthau 🇵🇰 I have read your story and it sounds amazing. Isn't it funny that people all across the world have similar stories? One thing is, however, still open to me: why would you discuss a 'Blitzkrieg' against India with your father? I mean, I know that there are a couple of Indian students here too. Isn't it dangerous to say something like this before so many people? I know exactly that you guys there have always had a stormy relationship, nevertheless, you guys may use your knowledge and intelligence to discourage people from such thoughts. It is the 21st century, united we would already be colonizing other planets.
> @Deleted User Thank you for taking the time to read my post, and also for your kind words. With regards to your comments about the whole 'Blitzkreig', I understand where you're coming from. Given the popularity of UoL in the Indian subcontinent, I am aware that there is likely to be a significant presence of Indian students on this server. My first instinct upon reading your comment was to apologise. However, I am not going to go down that route. Please allow me to explain why: (1) First of all, I feel the context is always key. As I mentioned in my most, I was 8 years old at the time of that discussion. An 8 year old does not possess the nuance to understand things like that you have mentioned. Also, while I did not mention the exact dates, I did say that these conversations happened in the late 1990s. This was a time of heightened tensions between the two countries. Both states had recently tested nuclear weapons, tensions were high at the borders, and in the pre-cable TV era, all information was spread through state-owned media. In the midst of this political climate, I think it was natural for a young student of history to ponder about the effectiveness of a military strategy in the likelihood of a war that always seemed to be around the corner.
Deleted User 21-Jul-20 11:07 PM
I come from Germany yet I found your unfinished comment about a possible war between Pakistan and India rather provocative, that's why I asked. I am pretty sure that a lot of people had the same thoughts, nevertheless, my position on this topic is unchanged. War is evil, it is even more evil when it comes out of the mouth of a little child.
morgenthau 🇵🇰 21-Jul-20 11:12 PM
(2) We live in a very polarised and highly charged climate. The cancel culture that has come to dominate our socio-political discourse has made it very difficult for people share their thoughts, ideas and stories. Perhaps, it is the same reason why I chose not to use my real name on this discussion server. Now I know that you were very polite in conveying your thoughts, encouraged me to spread positivity and did NOT ask me to apologise for my words, and I truly appreciate that. However, I feel that in a comunity of students, all ideas and thoughts should be up for debate, something that is advocated by the Chicago Principles (https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2018/12/21/chicago-principles-are-gold-standard-freedom-expression-campuses-opinion). Hence, I feel that in a climate where individuals are regularly made to apologise for what they might have said ages ago, me apologising for what I said as an 8 year old would only add it that, even if it is in the context of our small academic community. _ Lastly, people grow and learn with the passage of time, and I assure you I have gone through that process as well. While the idea of Blitzkreig stil fascinates me, I am much more aware about the horrific aftereffects of war to not ponder about their use by any state or group against another state or group. Over the past two decades of learning, unlearning and relearning, I have come to understand that the things that we have been taught at a young age do not necessraily stand the test of ideals and morals of a unified world. Once again, I would urge you to consider that those words were those of an 8 year old who was fascinated by the history of the two Great Wars (ironic name since no war should ever be considered great). So yes, let's move towards working together to colonise other planets. Mars seems like a good (and probable) start.

linh🇻🇳🇲🇾🇫🇷 24-Jul-20 03:02 AM
@Oscar 🇵🇪 the flexibility that the program offers helps my health and living situation. I graduated from highschool 3 years early but with mediocre results and didn't know what to do with my life. Grew up in a big city with few adult figures and little parental guidances so I've pretty much had the whole "college experience" and got tired of it before I turned 17. A little downturn in my family's financial situation and I headed to Europe for uni when I turned 18 instead of the States as had been planned out my entire schooling career. I dropped out of a grande école in France after a year, as it seemed like I was back in school with a bunch of unmotivated high school kids, whose only motives for studying was for the prospect of huge bucks after graduation. I was just not in the right crowd and I didn't like the mindset, needed more mental stimulation to quench my ridiculous intellectual thirst. It was also too expensive for the quality of the staffs and overall education. Going out to gain experience was discouraged; I felt limited. Overall, not for me. Studying at LSE gave me a lot of time to settle in France and deal with my many unaddressed/under-addressed mental abnormalities that have been causing me issues since I was a child (ADHD, anxiety, giftedness, mild OCD, non-24 sleep issues). It sounds like a lot but when one thing goes untreated for a long time, it leads to further complications. Overall I'm much healthier now, and studying at UOL had allowed me to go on a much needed self-discovering, self-discipline and centering and self-understanding journey. I'm doing a double-major thing now with French Studies at a local uni and I plan to start an 2-year apprenticeship in hospitality on my 3rd year at UOL. After that it sounds crazy, but I want to go into public policy and governance. (edited)

linh🇻🇳🇲🇾🇫🇷 04-Aug-20 09:36 AM
@Karma647 it's recognition prior learning, essentially allows you to transfer credits from any courses that you've done before provided that the syllabus matches. For me I've done the intro courses to econs, finance, accounting, marketing, stats and math at my previous institution, but was only able to transfer over econs as I failed quite a bit of the rest the year prior
linh🇻🇳🇲🇾🇫🇷 04-Aug-20 09:44 AM
@Karma647 finance is more like calculations, understanding monetary value in the present and future and therefore currency fluctuations, essentially the theory behind accounting. Accounting is more friendly towards anyone that wants to own a business really. Understanding the financial statements and so on. If you do trading or want to understand how to make the best out of your mortgage for example, and compare values between the likes and where to put your money, or eventually you wanna make strategic decisions in a financial institution, you'll need more finance (although you'll likely need to do the basics of both anyways). If you do handy works for a bank and/or just need the basics for doing your own business's paperwork, then accounting would kinda be your go-to. (edited)

@Ilsa Tariq Congratulations, Ilsa. Hope you're able to make the most of this opoortunity. Whenever you get the chance, could you please share the issue of Letters of Recommendation for Independent Students. At present, the university arranges ONE letter of recommendation of the leading institute of our program. So in my case, since I'm pursuing an EMFSS degree, they'll arrange a letter of recommendation from LSE's Dean of UOL International Programs. The problem is that let's suppose I'm applying for a masters at LSE, I would need TWO letters of recommendation, prefereably academic. This is a huge disadvantage for students who are independent. Based on what I've found on the VLE forums, one or two students in the past have even reached out to the Professor who authored the Student Guide of their module. Perhaps the university can come up with a solution to this so if you have let's say 70+ in an essay based module, or 85+ in a math based module, the instructor for that can give you a LoR as well? Or perhaps some other way. Would love to hear your thoughts on this, and also of others on this server.

Ilsa Tariq 14-Oct-20 01:11 AM

linh🇻🇳🇲🇾🇫🇷 14-Oct-20 03:22 AM
@linh🇻🇳🇲🇾🇫🇷 Hi. Could you also share the details of course weight to me. Cant figure out how an aggregate of 490 marks comes out.
@natc it's detailed in the program regulations
Here's mine and the courses that I plan to take
Essential they take 9 marks from your top 9 grades throughout the program, in which 100 courses only count up to 2 marks. So depending on the number of 100 courses that you take, you can divide them up accordingly. The aggregates of your 100 courses being the average of the two highest and average of the next two highest 100 modules. That's 2 marks maximum. (edited)
For me I only took 5 100s, in which 2 of them were half courses, so that's a total of 4 full 100 courses, which makes each count for .5 for me personally. Most people in the standard entry take more than this though, so it depends on what's your lowest score(s), that's the one that doesn't count (edited)
The 200 and 300 courses each count for 1 mark. So let's say next year or at the end of 3 years I have higher marks in some 200 or 300 courses, I can include them into my marking scales for 100s. Which means that to push my grades, I need to score higher than I did in my 100 modules so that the 200/300 courses replace my 2 mark of 100s, and that I should be aiming for my 100s to be counted as only 1 mark, with the lower scores being phased out.
It's different for everyone depending how many 100 courses you take, if you've taken more 200/300s, if you've had any APL, or if you're in the graduate entry route. Just follow the guidelines on the program regulations very closely (edited)
The aggregate is the sum of your 9 marks, averaged of any half courses included
1

linh🇻🇳🇲🇾🇫🇷 26-Oct-20 06:52 AM
Hey guys, just a quick warning word about the core management concepts online course in VLE. I know they took the hard copy of the study guide away this year but I'd recommend not trying to do it without the study guide and relying solely on the block reading on the VLE.
It skims out on really important concepts such as transaction costs that I'm sure will be of importance on the exams. If you choose to not go by the study guide then I suggest do the essential reading extremely thoroughly and also check out a few of the recommended readings for each chapter
The VLE online blocks are a much easier read and overly simplified compared to the rest of the materials
I just printed the study guide after going through a few chapters of the online blocks and it felt like I didn't know half of the terminologies when sitting in a exam lol
